# Docs First

Before writing or changing code in this repository, **read the relevant markdown files in `docs/`**. They are the source of truth for scope, priorities, robot roles, sensors, safety, and SDK usage.

Do not rely on memory or generic Cyberwave docs alone when this project already documents a decision.

## Documentation index

| File | Use when |
| --- | --- |
| `docs/hackathon-mvp-requirements.md` | MVP scope, P0/P1/P2 priorities, architecture, web UI, demo script, safety |
| `docs/robot-sensors-research.md` | Sensor capabilities, robot roles, hardware verification checklist |
| `docs/safeground_mvp_requirements.md` | SafeGround product scope, orchestration, adapters, SDK primitives (section 16), open questions |

## Workflow

1. Identify which doc(s) apply to the task.
2. Read the relevant sections (use search within `docs/` if needed).
3. Align the implementation with documented priorities and safety constraints.
4. If the change alters scope, robot behavior, or assumptions, **update the doc(s)** in the same session.
5. For SDK details not covered in `docs/`, cross-check [Cyberwave docs](https://docs.cyberwave.com/overview) and note any gap in project docs if it blocks the hackathon.

## Cyberwave SDK — SO-101 arm (reference)

Use this pattern for twin creation, studio transform, and joint control. Prefer `cw.affect("simulation")` or `cw.affect("live")` before sending commands to hardware.

```python
from cyberwave import Cyberwave

cw = Cyberwave()

# One-liner to create the twin for SO-101
so_101 = cw.twin("the-robot-studio/so101")

# Edit transform in the studio
so_101.edit_position(x=1, y=0, z=0.5)
so_101.edit_rotation(yaw=90)  # degrees

# Joint control
so_101.joints.arm_joint = 45  # degrees
```

Also documented in `docs/safeground_mvp_requirements.md` (section 16): `arm.joints.set("joint_name", value)`, `joints.list()`, `get_all()`. Validate exact joint names and twin slugs against the hackathon environment before live runs.

## Safety

- Work only with mock objects in controlled demo areas (see `docs/hackathon-mvp-requirements.md`).
- Use bounded, supervised robot motion; never touch targets classified as mine or dubbio with SO-101 unless explicitly marked safe in docs and demo setup.
